>The thing I find amusing about Missy's design is the only creatures with fingers like that IRL are insectivores
Could you list a few? When I look up insectivores and look for common traits, I find paws with long claws, which they seem to use for things like digging in termite mounds. I'm not seeing hands like those. I'm not seeing much in the way of hands with opposable thumbs at all in the animal kingdom outside of primates. When I look it up I see koalas, opossums, and giant pandas, maybe chameleons. Some birds have feet nimble enough to pick stuff up and manipulated it, and raccoons have anatomically very complex paw hands that are very dexterous with multiple opposable digits that can fold down over the middle of the paw to grasp and manipulate objects. Some animals with very long claws are insectivores, like anteaters, but some aren't, like sloths. I am fascinated by the question and hope everyone here doesn't mind.

They are tied for majority with elves.
Elves' early ancestors were underground dwellers, so they tended to mate often for more and more hands to dig the tunnels.
